17:42.380 --> 17:44.080
And here are your hosts.

17:48.620 --> 17:58.560
This is David Crews. And David Carson. Fantasy writer Robert E. Howard grew up in
the 1920s and the 1930s in the small Texas town of Cross Plains. But he wasn't

17:58.560 --> 18:07.220
like other small town boys. He kept to himself quite a bit. He read a lot and
used a vivid imagination to create his memorable heroic fantasies, foremost of

18:07.220 --> 18:15.720
which are the stories of Conan the Barbarian. Howard died in 1936, but some of
the people in Cross Plains still remember him clearly. We spoke with two of

18:15.720 --> 18:23.620
Howard's friends, Jack Scott, the editor of the Cross Plains newspaper, and
Leroy Butler, Howard's next-door neighbor. Butler remembers a time when he and

18:23.620 --> 18:31.620
Howard were still children, and they bought some swords from a mail-order
company in New York. But we ordered those things, and we'd get out in the

18:31.620 --> 18:44.120
backyard and wrap a bandana hankie around our heads like a pirate, and we'd get
out and fence with those things. Of course, we didn't dare, you know, hit each

18:44.120 --> 18:54.020
other with them, because they'd have gone through you. But we did that quite a
bit. We had an immense live oak tree in our backyard, and we'd get out there and

18:54.020 --> 18:59.380
shade of that old tree and pretend

18:59.380 --> 19:15.600
that we were back maybe in the dark ages or something, or in the time of the
Spanish main, things like that. But he had things like that on his mind all the

19:15.600 --> 19:24.420
time. Butler says that Robert was a loner dedicated to his writing. Robert never
married. He never seemed interested in girls.

19:27.560 --> 19:37.180
And he did have one girlfriend there in Cross Plains for a time. I'd see him out
in the car driving around once in a while. But I don't think that lasted long.

19:37.180 --> 19:54.520
He was just wrapped up in his work, writing those stories. And he had a glassed
-in back porch on the southeast side of the house there. And it wasn't too far

19:54.520 --> 20:05.080
from my mother's bedroom. And a lot of times at night, he'd wake her up with
that typewriter clacking, you know, at 1 or 2 o'clock in the morning. Some

20:05.080 --> 20:11.260
inspiration, he'd probably be laying there in bed and think of something, and
he'd get up and write it down right quick.

20:14.160 --> 20:27.060
And he just worked all the hours. Jack Scott also comments on Howard's unusual
personality. Howard was a little on the odd side. He wasn't intimate with very

20:27.060 --> 20:38.580
many people. He was rather aloof. But he was a big, robust man. To me, he was a
combination of Edgar Allen Poe and Jack London, if you can imagine that two

20:38.580 --> 20:52.220
together. In 1936, when Howard's mother was dying of a terminal illness, Howard
took his own life. I remember the morning he killed himself very well. I heard

20:52.220 --> 21:01.560
on the street that Robert Howard had just shot himself. But I immediately jumped
in my car and ran down there and got down there. And a few neighbors had

21:01.560 --> 21:13.900
gathered. It wasn't generally known over town, but the old justice of the peace
was standing there on the gallery, the front porch. And when I walked up, he

21:13.900 --> 21:23.920
called me and said, Come here, Jack. And I stepped up there, and he took me into
the bedroom. And he pointed to an old Underwood typewriter that had four lines

21:23.920 --> 21:36.660
written on it there. And Howard had, when he had been told that his mother
wouldn't live throughout the day, he went to this typewriter, wrote these four

21:36.660 --> 21:47.060
lines, and walked outside and sat down in his car and shot his head off. And
this old JP asked me what these four lines meant. They said, I'm sure you've

21:47.060 --> 21:55.960
read them, All fled, all done. So let me on the pyre. The feast is over. The
lamps expire. More about Robert E. Howard next time.

