22:52.720 --> 22:56.680
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

23:12.640 --> 23:17.800
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

23:20.620 --> 23:22.160
And here are your hosts.

23:26.700 --> 23:35.000
This is David Carson. And David Crews. Will Conan the Barbarian ever die, or will
he go on forever? A large portion of the fantasy section of bookstores these

23:35.000 --> 23:43.180
days is filled with books about Conan, the heroic barbarian created by the late
Robert E. Howard. Howard devised a mythical era for his hero and called it the

23:43.180 --> 23:51.760
Hyborian Age. The period falls somewhere between the fall of Atlantis and the
beginnings of recorded history. Conan is a giant barbarian from Cimmeria, a

23:51.760 --> 24:00.060
region to the north of the more civilized Hyborian kingdoms. With his huge
sword, he is an irresistible force that no man can stand up to. Howard wrote

24:00.060 --> 24:08.960
some 21 Conan stories in the 1930s, most published in the pulp magazine Weird
Tales. They trace the life of the barbarian from his teenage years to his later

24:08.960 --> 24:17.420
maturity when he became a king. The tales are full of lusty, bloody adventure,
pure escape fantasy that appeals to man's primal instincts. Conan battles

24:17.420 --> 24:26.260
warriors, sorcerers, and monsters of all shapes. He's a thief, a soldier, a
swashbuckling pirate, and a king. The Conan stories are so popular that a number

24:26.260 --> 24:33.120
of publishing houses have been putting them out. And a number of different
authors have been writing Conan stories. Howard left many gaps in the life of

24:33.120 --> 24:40.500
Conan, and various contemporary writers have been filling those gaps with
original stories. L. Sprague de Camp was the first author to do that. These

24:40.500 --> 24:49.440
stories done by other writers are called pastiches, and established writers such
as de Camp, Andrew J. Offutt, Poul Anderson, Lin Carter, and Bjorn Nyberg have

24:49.440 --> 24:57.660
done them. We went to Robert E. Howard's home territory, the Brownwood Cross
Plains area of west central Texas, to speak with Dr. Charlotte Laughlin and Dr.

24:57.820 --> 25:06.280
William Kreider. Dr. Laughlin has done research for a biography of Howard, and
Dr. Kreider teaches science fiction and fantasy at Howard Payne University. Dr.

25:06.440 --> 25:17.380
Kreider explains what a pastiche is. Well, in the sense that we've been talking
about it, it's where one writer takes a character and a world, like the Hyborian

25:17.380 --> 25:28.380
Age, created by another writer, and writes new stories with the same character
and the same setting. And he gets the full credit for the story, but the other

25:28.380 --> 25:43.340
writer has created the character and the historical setting. Also, de Camp did
something similar, where he took incomplete Howard stories and changed them into

25:43.340 --> 25:52.920
Conan stories, which would be a pastiche of a slightly different kind, but it's
the same principle operating.

26:01.780 --> 26:09.860
The biography of Howard, entitled Dark Valley Destiny, has been written by L.
Sprague de Camp and his wife Catherine, and will probably be out sometime in the

26:09.860 --> 26:17.900
next year. The book will mainly be a psychological study of Howard, which
attempts to explain why he wrote the kind of material he did. Conan has been so

26:17.900 --> 26:25.640
popular that a major movie about him, entitled Conan the Barbarian, is
premiering this week across the country. It was filmed in Spain by director John

26:25.640 --> 26:32.800
Milius and produced by De Laurentiis, and has muscle man Arnold
Schwarzenegger playing Conan. Early reports indicate that it does a marvelous

26:32.800 --> 26:39.920
job of conveying the atmosphere of sword and sorcery essential to a Conan
adventure. Laughlin and Kreider talk about the movie and about Conan's

26:39.920 --> 26:53.520
popularity. If this is a huge success, like Star Wars, let's say, that could
give even more impetus to this kind of thing, and we may see Howard going on

26:53.520 --> 27:04.580
forever with these pastiches being done by... I think it's possible that they
would be continued, because the original idea was to fill out Conan's life, you

27:04.580 --> 27:13.000
know, have his life completely covered by the pastiches from, I don't know if he
went to his boyhood, but certainly all of his adult life when he was an old King

27:13.000 --> 27:20.740
Conan. And it's already gone beyond that. They filled out his life, and then
they're going back to, you know, this stage in his life. He did such and such.

27:21.540 --> 27:30.500
So certainly they're not going to stop with what would be the chronological life
of Conan. So the potential to go on beyond is there. The potential to keep Conan

27:30.500 --> 27:34.960
alive and adventuring is definitely there. We should be hearing a lot more from
Conan.

